The next experiment I’d actually run

Before building hardware, I’d test whether the architecture has computational value in simulation.

Represent each node as:

S_i = (\theta_i,\ \omega_i,\ \phi_i,\ A_i,\ C_i,\ P_i)

where:

* \theta: orientation
* \omega: angular frequency
* \phi: phase
* A: amplitude
* C: coupling coefficient
* P: persistence

Then define local interaction rules and let the network evolve.

Measure:

* convergence time
* energy consumption (simulated)
* robustness to noise
* quality of solutions
* scalability

If it performs well on even one benchmark where existing methods struggle, you’ve identified something worth investigating further. If it doesn’t, you’ll learn why, and that informs the next iteration.

That’s how you “carry the letter to Garcia” in research: preserve the vision, but convert it into a sequence of questions that can be answered by evidence. If the idea has merit, that process strengthens it; if parts don’t hold up, the remaining core becomes clearer and more useful.